	Policy
In this model, the government is constituted by two distinct policymakers: the Fiscal Authority and an independent Central Bank. The Fiscal Authority is responsible for implementing subsidies, transfers, and taxes directed towards both households and firms. In contrast, the Central Bank holds the mandate to regulate nominal interest rates.

	Central Bank
The Central Bank can operate under the following regime:
r_t/r ̅ =(r_(t-1)/r ̅ )^(ρ_m ) (((π_t^C)/π ̅ )^(ϕ_π ) (y_t/y ̅ )^(ϕ_y ) )^(1-ρ_m )	(23)
In this regime, the central bank responds to inflation in the production sector (Core Inflation), while not paying attention of headline CPI inflation readings. This is motivated by the central bank’s inability to stabilise and affect the supply in the energy sector. 

The central bank also has an exogenously determined gross inflation target (π_t ) ̅. Since I do not assume the growth of the economy or energy supply, it only makes sense that the gross inflation target is set to 1. Thanks to this, in steady state, prices remain constant (prices of consumption goods and energy are equal) the allocation of consumption between energy and consumption goods stays the same. Moreover, this assumption simplifies the calibration of the model, as both consumption goods and energy have the same price and henceforth ω_c can represent the marginal share in the consumption basket. 

