The primary policy instruments for responding to energy shocks are subsidies directed toward Keynesian households, Ricardian households, and firms. This study examines these parameters and evaluates their impact on key macroeconomic variables.

3.4 Energy Market Equilibrium
In this economy, there is an exogenous and costless supply of energy E_t, which follows an AR(1) process: 
log⁡〖E_t=(1-ρ_E )  log⁡(E_t ) ̅  〗+ρ_E  log⁡〖E_(t-1)-z_t^E 〗	(26)
Where z_t^E~N(0,σ_E^2 ).
Moreover, the total demand for energy (from households and firms combined) has to be equal to the supply of energy, henceforth:
E_t=V_t^E+ςC_t^(K,E )+(1-ς) C_t^(R,E )	(28)
The price p_t^E is achieved through a process of Walrasian tâtonnement so that those quantities balance exactly. This implies that energy prices, contrary to non-energy consumption goods, are fully flexible. For computation and calibration purposes, I will assume that the steady-state energy price is equal to 1. In later sections of this paper, I will analyse the effects of a shock v_t^E on main macroeconomic variables. As we can see, the shock is i.i.d but it is being propagated into the energy supply. The size of the shock will be equal to one standard deviation (σ_E^2) of the shock process z_t^E.

4 Model Dynamics
4.1 Calibration Strategy 
In this paper, I will use all the quantitative parameters with their quarterly calibration. This ensures that the results obtained are comparable to the previous literature on the topic. To calibrate important structural country-specific parameters (Risk aversion coefficient σ; Inverse of Frisch elasticity ψ; Calvo Parameter θ; monetary policy parameters ϕ_π,ϕ_y,ρ_m, I turned to Poland-specific studies estimating those parameters using DSGE-VAR ([Borowska, 2011]; [Leszczyńska-Paczesna, 2020] or informed by Bayesian VAR impulse responses [Sobieraj, Metelski, 2021). I use Nisticò [2007] formula to determine the parameters in Rotemberg pricing framework. Models used in those papers do not differ in the fundamental structure of key macroeconomic mechanisms, and where they differed, it does not seem to matter, as estimate’ were relatively consistent across the aforementioned studies. 

Some calibration parameters are taken from measurements of the Polish economy, those include: government expenditure/GDP (g); Debt/GDP Ratio (d). In order to ensure comparability across countries, those data points are taken from the IMF [2024a; 2024b] and UN [2024]. Moreover, some calibration parameters stem from the literature consensus and henceforth are stated without any source (Discount Factor β; elasticity of substitution across goods varieties η_c; Depreciation Rate δ; Persistence of Energy Shock ρ_e). Fiscal policy responses to the government expenditure shock and debt are assumed to take the values of φ_d=0.3 ,φ_g=0.1, which are taken from Gali et al. [2007]. Estimation of the elasticity of substitution between energy consumption and non-energy consumption (η_c) and elasticity of substitution between energy and capital-labour bundle( η_p) has been the subject of an extended debate. The literature contains a wide range of estimates regarding the elasticity of substitution between production inputs. Higher estimates, like the one from Bodenstein et al. [2012] (0.42), are driven by structural econometric model estimates of the short-run price elasticity of oil demand. While Natal [2012] set this parameter at 0.3. Adjemian and Darracq Paries [2008] at 0.09 is on the low end of estimates. They use production functions that combine the Cobb-Douglas bundle of labour and capital, with energy, using a CES function. Both Erceg et al. [2024] and Auclert et al. [2023] deploy a similar production structure, and they estimate the elasticity to be around 0.1. 

When it comes to estimating the Marginal Consumption Weights (ω_c,ω_p ) and the necessity level of consumption ((C^E ) ̃ ) we face another difficult problem. This is because we cannot make a standard assumption that the marginal consumption weight (ω_c) is equal to the average consumption share, as long as the necessity consumption ((C^E ) ̃) is not equal to zero. Estimating those parameters would require really high-quality data. However, thanks to demand characterisation analysis (See section 3.1.3) and bearing in mind the calibration of price levels, we can see that ω_c is an asymptotic expenditure share. Using data from Bachmann et al. (2022), I will calibrate (C^E ) ̃=0.015 andω_c=0.035, as we can see that for top income bracket individuals, expenditure share decreases to around 0.035, while for poor households, the expenditure share is around 0.05. Those two factors combined motivate the household preferences. When it comes to estimating the production share, then again Erceg et al. (2022) and others (see Bachmann et al. [2022], Natal [2012], Stevens [2015]) estimate it to be around 0.05. Another fact that motivates this calibration is that it generates a realistic steady-steady allocation of energy going to households (around 37.4%) vs the actual 29.4% [Odyssey- Mure, 2024]. The true value is probably even closer to our steady state, as I assume that the government does not consume energy, which is an obvious simplification. 

Lastly, the fraction of Keynesian households (ζ) is set to 0.3, following the analysis by Gali et al. [2007]. The authors demonstrate that this value is the maximum while ensuring both the uniqueness and determinacy of the competitive equilibrium in the TANK model, regardless of the calibration of price stickiness. This outcome primarily arises because such a setting effectively precludes the existence of stationary sunspot equilibria.

[Table 1: Summary of Calibration Strategy.]

4.2 Energy Shock 
4.2.1 Aggregate Dynamics
Following the description of the model and calibration strategy, I can quantitatively analyse the effects of large and negative energy supply shocks on the economy. In order to demonstrate how key model features impact macroeconomic dynamics, I will compare the Baseline TANK (as described in previous sections) model with the Representative Agent New Keynesian (RANK), where we omit the heterogeneity of agents and the Homothetic TANK where we omit the necessity level of energy consumption. Those changes are equivalent to setting ζ=0.00 in the case of RANK and setting (C^E ) ̃=0.00 in the case of Homothetic TANK. In the case of Homothetic TANK, we, however, have to adjust the , such that in the steady state, energy consumption is the same in both models.

[Figure 2: Impulse Response Functions of Main Macroeconomic Variables (% deviation from the steady state).]

Figure 2 shows how key macroeconomic variables respond to an unexpected and negative energy supply shock that diminishes over time as an AR(1) process. When the energy supply, a good demanded by all agents in the economy, decreases, the standard law of demand leads to an increase in its price because both households and firms have strictly monotonic preferences for energy. The shock size has been calibrated so that the energy price rises by 40% in the baseline scenario. This surge in energy prices raises marginal costs of production, which results in a decline in the economy's output. In the baseline calibration, output drops by 3.7% (on impact). The contraction in economic activity, combined with higher energy costs, causes wages for workers to fall. Nonetheless, households respond by increasing their labour supply to smooth consumption, leading to a 1.2% rise in labour supplied. This additional labour helps to cushion the output decline somewhat. As households supply more labour, wages tend to decrease, and because the response is more intense in TANK, the wage fall there is also more significant. Consumption declines due to both reduced energy consumption and lower output. As marginal costs increase, prices generally go up, since they are usually set by adding a mark-up over marginal costs. This inflationary pressure prompts the central bank to raise interest rates to sustain price stability. 

Regarding the policy response, the central bank is able to increase the interest rate more significantly in the TANK model than in the RANK model, owing to the less pronounced decline in output. This leads to higher government expenditure on debt repayment, resulting in larger deficits relative to the RANK model. Given that tax policy is more responsive to debt servicing than to government spending, taxation increases sharply. An interesting observation is the prolonged impact of the shock, with hours worked taking over 40 quarters to return to steady-state levels. This extended adjustment period is attributed to the significant inertia within the tax system, which influences labour market conditions through the standard supply channel [Baxter and King, 1993].

When we comparatively analyse the responses of TANK and RANK, we are able to learn the importance of agent heterogeneity. The contraction in output is less severe in the baseline TANK model compared to the RANK model, primarily due to an increase in hours worked, which is predominantly driven by Keynesian households. Notably, heterogeneity appears to have a limited impact on inflation, whether considering headline (marginal) inflation, energy prices, or core inflation measures. The inflationary response in the TANK model is slightly muted, reflecting the smaller decline in production. 

[Figure 3: Demand for Production Factors (% deviation from the steady state).]

In Figure 3, we see how different production factors are impacted by the energy shock. Most severely impacted is the firm energy consumption, which falls the most (more than 30%). The response is broadly speaking uniform across different specifications. What is very important for the system is that the large hours' response seems to a large extent from the necessity level of energy consumption for Keynesian households. In homothetic-TANK and RANK, hours worked increase by around 0.6%, while in baseline calibration, the response is much more pronounced, with labour supply increasing by 1.2%. When we analyse both RANK (with non-homotheticity) and homothetic TANK, we can ‘decompose’ the labour response into household heterogeneity effect and non-homotheticity effect. As we can see, both of those effects yield similar labour responses to each other, suggesting that only the intersection can significantly increase the labour supply. As we will be able to see in the next Figure 4, this effect is large and profound and is the main driver behind a more moderate fall in output in the TANK model. The economic rationale for that mechanism is the way necessity consumption enters directly into the household budget constraint. It acts on the same channel as the increased lump-sum tax would. Therefore, households in baseline TANK have a compounded incentive to increase their labour supply, as both the price of the consumption basket increased, but also their necessity expenditure has increased, contributing to a higher response in hours worked. Missing this important channel might lead to wrong inferences and changes in optimal policy.

4.2.2 Utility Analysis
Figure 4 demonstrates factors that shape the utility of the households, that is, the hours worked and consumption. Gaps are percentage differences between Keynesian households and Ricardian households. 

[Figure 4: Impulse Response Functions of Utility and Utility Shaping Factors (% deviation from the steady state).]

As we can see from the left-most panel, when we introduce non-homotheticity, the overall impact on utility is changes in magnitude and sign. Without necessity consumption, Keynesian households obtain lower utility loss than Ricardian households and their situation is comparatively improved. This stems from the standard assumption in TANK literature [Galí et al., 2007] that the steady-state tax policy is welfare efficient, that is Keynesian households obtain taxes that equalise their consumption to Ricardian households. This implicitly means that their income is to some extent ‘independent’ of the current income conditions. In the non-homothetic case, the difference is again mainly driven by labour market response, which is more muted in the homothetic case. This is a theoretical result found in the economic literature Ravn & Sterk [2021], or in Auclert et al. [2023]. Future empirical studies, are needed to demonstrate this mechanism in Polish context with appropriate rigour empirically. A forthcoming study from Finland have shown a increase in labour supply provided by constrained households [Ahlvik et al., 2026]. 

Without necessity consumption, Keynesian households barely respond by increasing their hours worked, which contributes to the fact that we observe a positive utility gap. When we supplement the model with necessary energy consumption, however, the picture and dynamic change significantly. This has important implications for fiscal policy rules, as if the policymaker does not recognise the necessity of consumption, they might design a subsidy scheme that benefits the Ricardian households, which might actually decrease the total utility. 

Despite the smaller recession caused by a decrease in energy supply, the utility losses (as a % of Steady-state value) in the baseline TANK model are much larger than in RANK or homothetic TANK. Households have decreased utility by 1.8% on impact. Other calibrations have much less pronounced decreases in utility between 1.4% and 1.6%. This again highlights the importance of both household heterogeneity and non-homotheticity while designing the macroeconomic policy. This picture drives the point home that omitting the necessity consumption significantly impacts welfare loss, which might lead to underestimating the impact of energy shock on the economy. What we can also see is that Baseline TANK returns relatively faster to the steady state than does the RANK model. This can be understood through the lens of the factors that stabilise the utility. In both models, the restoration of energy supply to its steady-state value serves as a fundamental driver of economic recovery, though a more detailed examination of the underlying processes, as shown in Figure 3, reveals slightly different mechanisms of adjustment between the two frameworks.

The RANK model demonstrates an enhanced capacity to internalise the accelerated increase in firms' marginal costs. This internalisation process facilitates a more rapid economic adaptation to the energy shock. Conversely, the TANK model relies more on wage adjustments and fiscal policy responses to stabilise the economy.

5 Policy Rules 
After the discussion of the response of the main economic variables and agents in the economy, it is now time to analyse the policy rules. We do not solve a full Ramsey problem; instead, we restrict fiscal policy to use energy subsidies τ^i to achieve 3 distinct goals: output, inflation and welfare stabilisation. This is consistent with policymaker setting those under discretion, as opposed to commitment. Under discretion, the policymaker re-optimises in each period, taking private-sector expectations as given, and therefore chooses subsidies to maximise current-period welfare without internalising the dynamic effects of the policy path on future expectations. This stands in deliberate contrast to the full Ramsey (commitment) problem, which we explicitly set aside in favour of simple, implementable rules. The contemporaneous criterion is also symmetric with the output and inflation objectives in Sections 5.1–5.2, enabling direct comparisons across policy objectives.
 
I will consider varying objectives and the level of information available to the policymaker. In the full information scenario, the government can effectively differentiate between various household types and the production side of the economy, allowing them complete freedom to set τ_r, τ_k and τ_p as desired. In the partial information scenario, the government cannot distinguish between different households, but can still recognise the production side of the economy. This results in one less degree of freedom, leading to the constraint τ_r=τ_k meaning the government can only choose τ_h and τ_p. In the single subsidy scenario, the government is limited to setting only one type of subsidy. In practical terms, this could be seen as the government controlling an energy company and reducing prices by a single parameter: τ. 

Stabilisation is the primary objective of the policy function, and the variables to be stabilised depend critically on the object of stabilisation. In this analysis, stabilisation is defined as the minimisation of the variance of deviations from steady-state values. Formally, the model is linearised around the steady state, and the policy objective is to limit the squared deviations of endogenous variables from their steady states over the horizon of the impulse response functions (IRFs), which is set to 40 periods. The stabilisation problem consists of choosing a combination of subsidies (τ_r,τ_k,τ_p )  to minimise the variance of deviations of key endogenous macroeconomic variables (y_t,π_t^c,U_t ) from their respective steady states. The variable U_t denotes contemporaneous aggregate utility and is given by: 
U_t=ζ((C_t^K )^(1-σ)/(1-σ)-κ_L  (N_t^K )^(1+φ)/(1+φ))+(1-ζ)((C_t^R )^(1-σ)/(1-σ)-κ_L  (N_t^R )^(1+φ)/(1+φ))
Subsidies are adjusted to minimise a loss function defined over centred second moments of these variables, subject to the structural constraints of the model, as characterised by its first-order conditions.
5.1 Parameter Space 
A robust macroeconomic model must yield determinate solutions. Determinacy analysis of the baseline model shows that the main source of indeterminacy is the firm subsidy parameter, τ_p. When τ_p is too high under a negative energy supply shocknegative energy supply shock, firm energy demand exceeds the total supply of energy in the economy. In this case, prices fail to adjust sufficiently, causing demand to grow without bound yielding a situation of explosiveness in which the model has no stable equilibrium.; firm energy demand exceeds the total supply of energy in the economy, producing indeterminacy.  Price fails to adjust enough, and the demand explodes. To identify the determinate range, I use Monte Carlo simulations to explore the parameter space and assess model behaviour under various allocations. The results indicate that determinacy, essential for meaningful economic analysis and policy design, requires τ_p∈(0,0.85), while other parameters need no restrictions. Consequently, the subsidy analysis focuses on this range, ensuring all resulting allocations yield determinate and stable solutions.
5.2 Output and Core Inflation Stabilisation

5.2.1 Output Stabilisation
To minimise the deviations in the output, the government would need to set τ_p=0.768 and τ_k=τ_r=τ_h=0 or τ=0.762. This suggests that to stabilise output, large firm subsidies are needed. This is an expected result, as we know that the marginal rate of substitution between energy and capital-labour bundle is moderate, and hence, a decrease in production stems from an inability to make up for the losses. A substantial subsidy to firms would therefore stabilise the firm energy demand (V_t^E) and, through it, stabilise production. However, what is true for the firm is also true for the household; that is, when introducing those large subsidies, the decrease in energy supply is mostly felt by the households, which therefore experience a significant decrease in their utility. In fact, the government's effort to stabilise the real economy induces utility losses that are almost 4 times as large as the baseline scenario without any government intervention. Increased labour supply induced by the decreased utility from the household side, in the short term, acts stimulative for the total output and hence, despite the negative supply shock, the economy experiences temporary expansion. In the case of one subsidy policy, since all agents receive the discount, the underlying price (p_t^E) has to increase that much, to diminish household consumption, which results in an energy allocation similar to the full information and partial information scenarios. 

[Figure 5: Output, Core Inflation and Utility under different policies and the aim of output stabilisation. (% deviation from the steady state).]

The policy is moderately successful in achieving its aim: full and partial information scenarios can diminish the decrease in output by almost 60% and an impact. They are also successful in slaying the core inflation by 0.6 p.p. on impact. Providing one subsidy is much less efficient, as the output is indeed established, but the fall decreased only by 0.4%. Utility experienced by the agents in the one-subsidy scenario is similar (outside of a few first periods) to full and partial information scenarios. Hence, one could make the argument that if the government is unable to discriminate the use of energy in the economy, the benefits of stabilising the economy are very limited and the costs to the utility are quite sizable. 

5.2.1 Core Inflation Stabilisation
In order to stabilise the core inflation, the government should pursue a policy that is similar to output stabilisation. In this model, one could even view the problem as a dual problem, with one set of tools being able to tackle both problems. To stabilise core inflation the policymaker would need to set τ_p=0.769 and τ_k=τ_r=τ_h=0 or τ=0.767. Slightly higher in the case of output stabilisation. It aims to decrease the marginal costs of the firm, which translates to decreased prices. By providing those generous subsidies, the firm is effectively shielded from energy price increases. Just before the 10th quarter after the shock, with expanding output, the economy dives even into slight deflation. This, however, is quickly reversed, and core inflation increases above the steady-state level. With increased labour supply, firms can offer lower wages, and henceforth, it is able to increase production over the steady-state level. This limits the core inflation in the economy as costs to firms for a brief period of time are lower than before the shock. Providing one subsidy is much less effective, especially if one analyses the effect on impact. In terms of inflation, there's close to no reduction in core inflation, and the decrease in output is quite close to no baseline. However, one subsidy quite quickly replicates the dynamic of more targeted approaches. This is because of the fact that when the government sets a one subsidy, most of its benefits are harvested by the production side, as they constitute more than 60% of total energy consumption. 

[Figure 6: Output, Core Inflation and Utility under different policies and the aim of Core Inflation stabilisation (% deviation from the steady state).]

The policy is moderately successful in achieving its aim: Full and Partial information scenarios can diminish the rise in core inflation by almost 40% on impact (by 0.7 pp). One subsidy offers close to no inflation protection on impact; it is, however, more efficient in bringing the inflation down quicker. 

5.3 Welfare Stabilisation 
I now turn to welfare stabilisation, where the fiscal authority chooses the subsidy coefficients to minimise fluctuations in contemporaneous household welfare. In line with the stabilisation criterion used throughout this section, welfare stabilisation is defined as minimising the variance of deviations of aggregate (instantaneous) utility from its steady state over the IRF horizon. 
[Figure 7: Output, Core Inflation and Utility under different policies and the aim of Welfare Stabilisation (% deviation from the steady state).]
Compared with output and core-inflation stabilisation, the welfare objective produces qualitatively different policy prescriptions: ‘optimal’ rules shift support away from firms and toward households (especially constrained households), with the aim of smoothing consumption and limiting the welfare loss. These “best” welfare-targeting rules reduce peak utility losses by more than 40%, but at the cost of higher macroeconomic volatility. By cushioning consumption, the policy dampens the endogenous labour-supply response that otherwise helps stabilise output after an energy shortage, so the recession becomes deeper and core inflation rises modestly. The associated fiscal expansion increases public debt substantially (peaking at several multiples of the baseline response), which later requires higher taxes and induces a stronger monetary tightening to maintain price stability. 
The effectiveness of welfare stabilisation depends crucially on the information available to the government. Under full information, the government can target subsidies to Keynesian households, effectively redistributing resources away from Ricardian households by setting, for example, τ_k=1.000 and τ_r=τ_p=0.000. Under partial information, when household types cannot be distinguished, welfare improvements require broad-based household support that is τ_h=1.000 and τ_p=0.000. While both strategies improve welfare, both operate through a common “disincentive” channel: by relaxing the consumption squeeze, they weaken the labour-supply margin that typically cushions output during the shock, thereby amplifying the downturn.
6 Conclusions
In this paper, I built a closed economy model with an exogenous energy supply, household heterogeneity, a non-homothetic utility function and New Keynesian features. Through the lenses of this model, I analysed the energy supply contraction calibrated to fit the observed market conditions after the Russian invasion of Ukraine. I was able to analyse the response of the main macroeconomic variables to this shock. The analysis shows that a shock of this size scars the economy for an extended period and causes a 3.7 % reduction in GDP and an increase in core inflation by 1.2%, while the marginal headline inflation increases by 2.8%. This positions my estimates slightly higher than previous studies on that matter. 

One key insight from my paper is that non-homotheticity matters significantly for macroeconomic dynamics. As we have seen, without this feature, the labour supply response of constrained households is much more muted, which carries significant implications for output stabilisation and utility experienced by those agents. Thus, this paper hopes to direct any future research to include those features in their models. Since a standard cost-push shock can approximate the nature of the shock, one finds that trying to stabilise the core inflation is the most effective in minimising the contraction and at a cost of welfare loss. 

Moreover, aside from a positive analysis of energy shocks on the economy, this paper aimed to provide a useful and rigorous normative analysis of optimal fiscal response to energy shocks. Best policy for welfare stabilisation does not coincide with the optimal policy for output or inflation stabilisation. Hence, the government faces a trade-off between stabilising the real economy and minimising losses for households. Moreover, as demonstrated in Section 5, those goals are antipodes of each other. The research also uncovered a large potential for subsidies to influence macroeconomic dynamics. If the government aims to stabilise the output and core inflation and implements the optimal firm subsidies, it can reduce the fall in output by 60% and core inflation by 40%. This policy, however, is significantly exacerbating the loss of utility, as households are left with little energy for their consumption. 

